  "prompt": "Why are there two capital letters in the surname McCall?",
  "response": "The surname \"McCall\" includes two capital letters due to its etymology and the conventions of naming in English, particularly in names of Scottish or Irish origin.\n\n1. **\"Mc\" Prefix**: The \"Mc\" in \"McCall\" is a prefix that means \"son of\" in Gaelic. It is a common element in many surnames of Scottish and Irish origin, such as McDonald, McCarthy, and McGregor. Historically, \"Mc\" is an abbreviation of the Gaelic word \"mac,\" which means \"son.\"\n\n2. **Capitalization Rules**: In English, it is customary to capitalize the first letter of a surname, regardless of its origin. Since the \"Mc\" prefix is considered an integral part of the name and not a separate word, the \"M\" is capitalized. The \"C\" in \"Call\" is also capitalized because it is the first letter of the second part of the surname. \n\nThus, the combination of these rules results in the two capital letters in \"McCall.\" This convention applies to other \"Mc\" surnames as well, such as \"McDonald,\" \"McKinley,\" and \"McAllister.\"",
